Here&#x27;s a trivial example of what I mean by strong vs. weak typing in dynamic languages:<p>Python (strongly typed):<p><pre><code>    >>>1 + &quot;1&quot;
    Traceback (most recent call last):
    File &quot;<stdin>&quot;, line 1, in <module>
    TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: &#x27;int&#x27; and &#x27;str&#x27;
</code></pre>
Ruby (also strongly typed):<p><pre><code>    irb(main):001:0> 1 + &quot;1&quot;
    TypeError: String can&#x27;t be coerced into Fixnum
            from (irb):1:in `+&#x27;
            from (irb):1
            from C:/Ruby193/bin/irb:12:in `<main>&#x27;
</code></pre>
PHP (weakly typed):<p><pre><code>    echo 1 + &quot;1&quot;;
    2

</code></pre>
Perl (also weakly typed):<p><pre><code>    print 1 + &quot;1&quot;;
    2</code></pre>
